Event emitters are everywhere — in Node.js, in the DOM, in frontend frameworks. But most implementations are loosely typed. You can emit an event with the wrong payload and TypeScript won't catch it.
Let's fix that by building a fully type-safe event emitter from scratch.
## The Goal
We want an event emitter where:
- Event names are constrained to a known set
- Each event has a specific payload type
- Emitting an event with the wrong payload is a compile error
- Listeners receive correctly typed arguments
```typescript
// This is what we're building toward
const emitter = new TypedEmitter<{
  login: { userId: string; timestamp: number };
  logout: { userId: string };
  error: { message: string; code: number };
}>();

emitter.on("login", (data) => {
  console.log(data.userId);    // typed as string
  console.log(data.timestamp); // typed as number
});

emitter.emit("login", { userId: "abc" }); // Error: missing timestamp
emitter.emit("unknown", {});              // Error: unknown event
```
## Step 1: Define the Interface
We start with a generic interface that maps event names to their payload types:
```typescript
type EventMap = Record<string, any>;

type EventHandler<T = any> = (payload: T) => void;
```
`EventMap` will be the type parameter users provide — an object where keys are event names and values are payload types.
## Step 2: The Core Class
```typescript
class TypedEmitter<Events extends EventMap> {
  private handlers = new Map<keyof Events, EventHandler[]>();

  on<K extends keyof Events>(event: K, handler: EventHandler<Events[K]>): void {
    const existing = this.handlers.get(event) ?? [];
    existing.push(handler as EventHandler);
    this.handlers.set(event, existing);
  }

  off<K extends keyof Events>(event: K, handler: EventHandler<Events[K]>): void {
    const existing = this.handlers.get(event) ?? [];
    this.handlers.set(
      event,
      existing.filter((h) => h !== handler)
    );
  }

  emit<K extends keyof Events>(event: K, payload: Events[K]): void {
    const existing = this.handlers.get(event) ?? [];
    for (const handler of existing) {
      handler(payload);
    }
  }
}
```
The magic is in `K extends keyof Events`. This constrains each method to only accept keys from the event map, and `Events[K]` resolves to the corresponding payload type.
