## Step 4: Usage Examples
Define your events as an interface for better readability:
```typescript
interface AppEvents {
  "user:login": { userId: string; role: "admin" | "user" };
  "user:logout": { userId: string };
  "notification": { message: string; type: "info" | "error" | "success" };
  "theme:change": { theme: "light" | "dark" };
}

const bus = new TypedEmitter<AppEvents>();

// Fully typed — IDE autocompletes event names and payload fields
bus.on("user:login", (data) => {
  console.log(`${data.userId} logged in as ${data.role}`);
});

bus.on("theme:change", (data) => {
  document.documentElement.dataset.theme = data.theme;
});

// Correct
bus.emit("notification", {
  message: "Welcome!",
  type: "success",
});

// Type error: 'warning' is not assignable to 'info' | 'error' | 'success'
bus.emit("notification", {
  message: "Oops",
  type: "warning",
});
```
---
## Comparison with Untyped Version
> An untyped event emitter is like a function that accepts `any` — it works until it doesn't. A typed event emitter catches bugs at compile time, documents your event contracts, and gives you autocomplete for free.
With an untyped emitter, these bugs would only surface at runtime:
```typescript
// Untyped — no errors, but broken at runtime
emitter.on("logIn", handler);          // typo in event name
emitter.emit("login", "wrong payload"); // wrong payload shape
emitter.emit("login");                  // missing payload entirely
```
With our typed emitter, all three are caught by the compiler before the code ever runs.
